00:12:24,417 --> 00:12:26,458
The Crucible maps are so good at this.

266
00:12:27,399 --> 00:12:28,900
In the opening mission, Homecoming,

267
00:12:29,140 --> 00:12:31,361
it relies heavily on voiceovers and HUD.

268
00:12:32,322 --> 00:12:34,463
As a result of this, your Ghost and Vanguards

269
00:12:34,543 --> 00:12:37,625
forego some opportunities to directly characterize themselves.

270
00:12:38,485 --> 00:12:40,587
They actively direct your player through the map.

271
00:12:41,967 --> 00:12:44,229
This undermines the immersive feel of Agency.

272
00:12:44,829 --> 00:12:47,831
As a result, the storyline must keep raising the stakes

273
00:12:48,151 --> 00:12:50,112
in order to continue to have an impact on the player.

274
00:12:51,374 --> 00:12:54,297
To some extent, as a designer, you must reward your player

275
00:12:54,337 --> 00:12:56,840
for pouring their own thoughts into their experience.

276
00:12:57,561 --> 00:13:00,143
If you set a standard that ceilings are rewarding

277
00:13:00,163 --> 00:13:02,466
and worthwhile to look at, you'll train your player

278
00:13:02,826 --> 00:13:04,288
to use that information actively.

279
00:13:04,988 --> 00:13:06,990
If you mail it in, you're likely to lose

280
00:13:07,010 --> 00:13:08,292
a little bit of trust with the player.

281
00:13:08,552 --> 00:13:09,513
It's kind of like sig figs.

282
00:13:11,415 --> 00:13:13,357
How do architects build these expectations?

283
00:13:13,761 --> 00:13:16,603
We'll go through a quick study noting specific elements

284
00:13:16,643 --> 00:13:17,444
of their impacts.

285
00:13:18,205 --> 00:13:19,306
And for the sake of this talk,

286
00:13:19,546 --> 00:13:21,868
architecture can be described through its materiality,

287
00:13:22,048 --> 00:13:24,030
adjacency, figure, light, and scale.

288
00:13:25,271 --> 00:13:28,493
More complex ideas such as proportion and ratio

289
00:13:28,733 --> 00:13:30,795
can be extrapolated from scale, for instance.

290
00:13:32,156 --> 00:13:35,259
Zaha Hadid uses the Contemporary Arts Center in Cincinnati

291
00:13:35,359 --> 00:13:36,560
to make art accessible.

292
00:13:37,200 --> 00:13:40,723
She uses a variety of tactics to achieve that accessibility,

293
00:13:41,184 --> 00:13:42,805
tackling it from different directions.

294
00:13:44,095 --> 00:13:45,736
So we'll take a moment to get acquainted

295
00:13:45,776 --> 00:13:46,777
with Hadid's masterpiece.

296
00:13:57,426 --> 00:14:00,409
Hadid ushers in the public by continuing this concrete

297
00:14:00,449 --> 00:14:03,271
from the sidewalk up the building in the wall.

298
00:14:04,633 --> 00:14:05,994
The gesture allows the concrete

299
00:14:06,034 --> 00:14:07,715
to characterize itself through texture.

300
00:14:08,176 --> 00:14:09,777
It's scored and rough at the sidewalk

301
00:14:09,817 --> 00:14:10,798
and honed in the lobby.

302
00:14:11,584 --> 00:14:16,007
And it has this formwork texture as it turns up into the wall as a structural material.

303
00:14:17,147 --> 00:14:20,749
The massing of the building relies on sliding boxes indicating function.

304
00:14:21,430 --> 00:14:24,532
She shows how exhibition spaces are laid out via the facade.

305
00:14:25,052 --> 00:14:29,475
Direct sunlight isn't good for art, therefore the space will be devoid of functional windows.

306
00:14:30,595 --> 00:14:34,517
This indicates individual collections and creates a hierarchy for their understanding

307
00:14:35,278 --> 00:14:36,058
and relationships.

308
00:14:37,612 --> 00:14:39,313
Natural light indicates public space.

309
00:14:39,833 --> 00:14:42,174
It's completely glazed and not just punched openings.

310
00:14:42,614 --> 00:14:44,195
The vertical scale of the public space

311
00:14:44,295 --> 00:14:45,616
also allows for natural light

312
00:14:45,636 --> 00:14:46,896
to reach deep into the structure.

313
00:14:47,517 --> 00:14:51,599
And I'll have you note that the entire wall is that window.

314
00:14:51,679 --> 00:14:52,679
It's a curtain wall.

315
00:14:53,000 --> 00:14:56,261
And it goes up that chasm that is the stairwell

316
00:14:56,481 --> 00:14:57,262
that you'll see here.

317
00:14:58,022 --> 00:15:01,664
The exaggerated lighting contrasts the public space

318
00:15:01,764 --> 00:15:04,886
from the exhibit areas, which cannot be naturally lit.

319
00:15:05,635 --> 00:15:08,496
This provides a subversive cue for the occupant

320
00:15:08,556 --> 00:15:12,597
to speak quietly or move slowly in gallery spaces,

321
00:15:13,218 --> 00:15:15,218
while still providing a visual relationship

322
00:15:15,278 --> 00:15:16,619
to that vertical circulation.

323
00:15:18,019 --> 00:15:19,920
So there's a lot of moving pieces in this one,

324
00:15:20,000 --> 00:15:22,201
and they all work to make art seem more accessible.

325
00:15:23,016 --> 00:15:26,077
Hadid pursues motive from a variety of angles

326
00:15:26,437 --> 00:15:28,078
and uses multiple design tools.

327
00:15:28,758 --> 00:15:30,719
This adds to the impact and legibility,

328
00:15:31,199 --> 00:15:34,541
but also takes on an opportunity for improvement

329
00:15:34,741 --> 00:15:36,882
for future architects to use it as inspiration.

330
00:15:38,543 --> 00:15:41,704
We'll analyze three games, two AAA titles,

331
00:15:41,764 --> 00:15:43,645
and one of them is indie, but pretty well known.

332
00:15:43,665 --> 00:15:46,066
I chose popular games for the case studies

333
00:15:46,126 --> 00:15:48,127
such that most of the audience will be familiar

334
00:15:48,167 --> 00:15:49,107
with the story and the lore.

335
00:15:51,143 --> 00:15:52,985
These games hold architecture accountable

336
00:15:53,405 --> 00:15:55,107
for different aspects of world building,

337
00:15:55,287 --> 00:15:57,689
and I'll break down the opportunities they chose to take

338
00:15:57,709 --> 00:15:59,271
as well as a few they might have missed.

339
00:16:00,271 --> 00:16:01,813
Breath of the Wild uses architecture

340
00:16:01,873 --> 00:16:04,235
to communicate cultural values and history.

341
00:16:04,855 --> 00:16:08,599
Fallout 3 uses it to cohesively tell a nonlinear story.

342
00:16:09,560 --> 00:16:13,263
Inside uses it in lieu of dialogue and text to tell a story.

343
00:16:13,963 --> 00:16:15,865
FYI, there will be spoilers.

344
00:16:17,106 --> 00:16:18,247
I'll start with Breath of the Wild.

345
00:16:19,457 --> 00:16:21,978
My favorite part of this game was seeing the villages.

346
00:16:22,479 --> 00:16:23,920
They established Link as a visitor,

347
00:16:24,120 --> 00:16:25,881
which adds to the authenticity.

348
00:16:26,462 --> 00:16:28,203
The lore has been built up by preceding

349
00:16:28,243 --> 00:16:29,404
Legend of Zelda games,

350
00:16:29,604 --> 00:16:31,665
but designers don't rely on that alone.

351
00:16:32,986 --> 00:16:35,348
Each village requires Link to earn an augment to reach

352
00:16:35,428 --> 00:16:37,510
or move through the area, creating a destination

353
00:16:37,550 --> 00:16:39,311
as opposed to something you just stumble upon,

354
00:16:40,492 --> 00:16:42,613
which overall is a very successful strategy

355
00:16:42,673 --> 00:16:43,574
for an open world game.

356
00:16:44,074 --> 00:16:46,056
In fact, the open nature of this world

357
00:16:46,497 --> 00:16:48,737
has created an emphasis on profile

358
00:16:48,958 --> 00:16:50,918
as a defining navigational feature.

359
00:16:51,799 --> 00:16:53,839
For instance, the stables look like horses.

360
00:16:54,240 --> 00:16:55,460
If you see them from a distance,

361
00:16:55,660 --> 00:16:57,341
you can tell you need to put your horse there.

362
00:16:57,761 --> 00:16:58,901
You're drawn to its profile,

363
00:16:59,922 --> 00:17:02,183
which actually exists in real life architecture,

364
00:17:02,223 --> 00:17:03,783
but it's not nearly as effective.

365
00:17:04,303 --> 00:17:07,004
Architecture parlant, or speaking architecture,

366
00:17:07,404 --> 00:17:09,085
visually describes its own function.

367
00:17:09,865 --> 00:17:12,426
Modern parlant has become synonymous

368
00:17:12,446 --> 00:17:14,487
with these literal recreations of profile.

369
00:17:15,572 --> 00:17:16,813
It's an attention-hungry move.

370
00:17:18,014 --> 00:17:19,035
And the worst part about it

371
00:17:19,055 --> 00:17:21,116
is that they're just boxes on the inside.

372
00:17:21,136 --> 00:17:24,559
That's just like a concrete sculpture

373
00:17:24,599 --> 00:17:25,880
that's been put over a box.

374
00:17:26,560 --> 00:17:27,081
It's gross.

375
00:17:29,133 --> 00:17:30,374
But Breath of the Wild commits to it,

376
00:17:30,854 --> 00:17:33,455
which allows the player to get a little bit more information

377
00:17:33,515 --> 00:17:34,235
out of the skyline.

378
00:17:34,875 --> 00:17:37,936
It's composed of shapes that are already recognizable

379
00:17:38,296 --> 00:17:40,777
that can provide a meaning to things

380
00:17:41,137 --> 00:17:42,537
before you have to learn about them.

381
00:17:42,917 --> 00:17:44,398
This gives the player agency,

382
00:17:44,878 --> 00:17:47,158
allowing inherent recognition skills to pay off.

383
00:17:49,184 --> 00:17:51,686
It's also used as a primary design feature

384
00:17:51,786 --> 00:17:52,747
for the Divine Beasts.

385
00:17:53,167 --> 00:17:55,689
They have a cohesive model with the interior

386
00:17:55,749 --> 00:17:57,511
adhering to the exterior envelope

387
00:17:58,151 --> 00:17:59,632
and that makes it way better.

388
00:17:59,853 --> 00:18:02,255
Actually, it creates this great exquisite corpse

389
00:18:02,315 --> 00:18:04,456
because you can even rotate the parts around.

390
00:18:06,658 --> 00:18:08,219
So we'll focus on the Rito Village,

391
00:18:08,299 --> 00:18:10,461
which is elevated by a nearby landscape.

392
00:18:11,530 --> 00:18:13,811
The divine beast is perched at the top of the spire,

393
00:18:13,951 --> 00:18:16,452
just like a bird, and the air drafts in the area

394
00:18:16,512 --> 00:18:19,174
pick up, similar to turbulence around real mountains.

395
00:18:22,436 --> 00:18:24,777
The village is lightweight wood frame construction.

396
00:18:25,697 --> 00:18:27,078
Fabric is a cladding material,

397
00:18:27,238 --> 00:18:30,260
which is uniquely advantaged in virtual architecture,

398
00:18:30,960 --> 00:18:33,461
and ritos, like birds, can fly,

399
00:18:33,542 --> 00:18:35,162
so wind direction is important to them.

400
00:18:35,523 --> 00:18:38,024
So feathers and fabric could feasibly serve a purpose.

401
00:18:39,225 --> 00:18:43,126
This allows visual correlation also to fuselages and gliders.

402
00:18:45,227 --> 00:18:47,908
And it's great considering how that contrasts the Goron's

403
00:18:48,168 --> 00:18:49,549
heavy timber construction.

404
00:18:50,029 --> 00:18:51,790
And actually, this is something we use in real life.

405
00:18:51,810 --> 00:18:54,631
A heavy timber is actually fire resistant.

406
00:18:54,751 --> 00:18:56,271
It creates a char around the outside,

407
00:18:57,212 --> 00:19:00,433
which prevents it from burning down as easily as lightweight

408
00:19:00,453 --> 00:19:01,313
wood frame construction.

409
00:19:01,982 --> 00:19:05,023
So it works twofold as the Gorons actually have very large hands

410
00:19:05,463 --> 00:19:08,464
and would most likely not care to articulate their handrails

411
00:19:08,484 --> 00:19:09,404
with fine details.

412
00:19:10,605 --> 00:19:13,086
So there's a lot of ways the level characterizes itself.

413
00:19:13,906 --> 00:19:16,347
But it also manages to foreshadow events as well.

414
00:19:17,287 --> 00:19:19,788
Just like movies, the level designers and environment

415
00:19:19,868 --> 00:19:21,989
artists decorated these scenes with props.

416
00:19:22,869 --> 00:19:25,350
It's exceptionally impressive that these

417
00:19:25,390 --> 00:19:28,051
work after giving the camera controls to a player.

418
00:19:31,312 --> 00:19:34,074
The profile of the hut is bell-shaped and framed out of wood,

419
00:19:34,414 --> 00:19:36,275
which ends up looking like a birdcage,

420
00:19:36,695 --> 00:19:39,177
but it also matches the profile of that shrine

421
00:19:39,237 --> 00:19:41,038
more closely than any of the other buildings.

422
00:19:41,979 --> 00:19:45,662
This introduces the concept as what we call a dialectic,

423
00:19:46,022 --> 00:19:47,623
providing two ends of the spectrum,

424
00:19:47,863 --> 00:19:50,425
embedded stone versus elevated wood frame.

425
00:19:51,747 --> 00:19:54,209
And the concept of primitive hut is taught this way

426
00:19:54,509 --> 00:19:55,570
by two warring concepts.

427
00:19:55,991 --> 00:19:58,733
Perrault and Logier, on opposite ends of the spectrum,

428
00:19:59,153 --> 00:20:01,675
Perrault proposes that architecture started

429
00:20:01,735 --> 00:20:03,076
with a hut embedded in the earth.

430
00:20:03,116 --> 00:20:05,017
We consider this vernacular architecture

431
00:20:05,118 --> 00:20:07,680
or architecture without architects.

432
00:20:08,940 --> 00:20:11,142
Logier proposes that it happened the first time

433
00:20:12,443 --> 00:20:14,064
columns and entablature were used.

434
00:20:14,585 --> 00:20:15,586
But if this was the case,

435
00:20:15,646 --> 00:20:16,887
I don't know if that's happened yet.

436
00:20:17,007 --> 00:20:18,248
I haven't seen trees do that.

437
00:20:20,643 --> 00:20:24,706
Introducing both allows that profile to work in two ways

438
00:20:25,046 --> 00:20:27,168
and allows the player to fill in gaps,

439
00:20:27,668 --> 00:20:31,010
allowing some indication of the origin of that design.

440
00:20:32,291 --> 00:20:34,392
And as with every great accomplishment,

441
00:20:34,432 --> 00:20:36,934
there's always some way to evolve or improve the concept.

442
00:20:37,534 --> 00:20:40,296
So I'd say the next step would be to create slightly more

443
00:20:40,336 --> 00:20:42,217
varied typologies from the exterior.

444
00:20:42,877 --> 00:20:45,039
Providing exterior variety to the huts

445
00:20:45,119 --> 00:20:46,780
could allow more characterization

446
00:20:47,040 --> 00:20:49,621
and create a spectrum of viable Rideau style huts.

447
00:20:50,955 --> 00:20:52,816
They're not distinctive from the exterior,

448
00:20:52,936 --> 00:20:55,616
which is odd as they're not intended to be manufactured.

449
00:20:56,156 --> 00:20:58,917
Precise, perhaps, but the organic nature of the layout

450
00:20:58,957 --> 00:21:02,897
would also indicate that it's not the intended takeaway.

451
00:21:04,158 --> 00:21:06,118
Shops and interactive huts require you

452
00:21:06,138 --> 00:21:08,518
to pass through the threshold to distinguish function.

453
00:21:08,998 --> 00:21:10,799
This problem is, of course, alleviated

454
00:21:10,879 --> 00:21:14,699
by showing certain items for sale

455
00:21:14,719 --> 00:21:16,700
or these little chick hammocks, which are kinda cute.

456
00:21:17,800 --> 00:21:19,400
They use colored textiles as well

457
00:21:19,440 --> 00:21:20,420
to customize the interior.

458
00:21:21,458 --> 00:21:23,421
So as I mentioned before, Breath of the Wild

459
00:21:23,461 --> 00:21:25,143
does an excellent job introducing

460
00:21:25,163 --> 00:21:26,164
a variety of cultures.

461
00:21:26,785 --> 00:21:28,868
It provides comparable design moments

462
00:21:29,088 --> 00:21:31,011
to demonstrate nuanced information

463
00:21:31,592 --> 00:21:33,635
that can be distinguished between different villages

464
00:21:33,695 --> 00:21:33,975
as well.

465
00:21:36,190 --> 00:21:38,950
Moving on to Fallout 3, it was an ambitious reboot

466
00:21:38,990 --> 00:21:40,230
to an isometric series.

467
00:21:40,971 --> 00:21:44,471
It introduces concrete visualizations

468
00:21:44,571 --> 00:21:46,772
to an already established world, which is hard.

469
00:21:47,392 --> 00:21:49,932
The series is laden with lore and subplots

470
00:21:50,072 --> 00:21:51,973
which allow an experience to become

471
00:21:52,353 --> 00:21:53,873
more or less catered to each player.

472
00:21:54,473 --> 00:21:56,814
The landmark buildings are where the level designers

473
00:21:56,974 --> 00:21:58,574
chose to convey more abstract goals,

474
00:21:58,674 --> 00:22:02,235
so that's what I'm gonna be using as a specific critique.

475
00:22:02,815 --> 00:22:08,518
And not meant to negativity, but there are a lot of reasonable decisions that I believe

476
00:22:08,558 --> 00:22:11,901
led to a less than impactful location, 10 penny tower.

477
00:22:12,761 --> 00:22:14,302
I think there's a lot we can learn from this, though.

478
00:22:14,722 --> 00:22:17,144
So I'll start with the datum of expectation.

479
00:22:18,124 --> 00:22:20,046
Megaton had a lot of roles in this game.

480
00:22:20,386 --> 00:22:22,327
Primarily, it establishes that datum.

481
00:22:23,088 --> 00:22:28,031
It uses materials and layout to convey a concept of makeshift space planning.

482
00:22:29,214 --> 00:22:31,995
They also established the distinction between friendly

483
00:22:32,035 --> 00:22:34,416
and hostile settlements by walling the city off.

484
00:22:35,456 --> 00:22:37,817
Circular walled cities historically have indicated

485
00:22:37,837 --> 00:22:42,058
a culturally important epicenter, which is true in Megaton.

486
00:22:42,658 --> 00:22:44,278
Everything has a view of that bomb,

487
00:22:44,558 --> 00:22:45,939
centrally located in the city.

488
00:22:46,679 --> 00:22:48,680
It showcases constraints of new cities,

489
00:22:49,180 --> 00:22:53,101
lacking means to fabricate and time to design and construct.

490
00:22:53,741 --> 00:22:55,522
This contributes to the characterization

491
00:22:55,602 --> 00:22:56,922
of the industrious wastelanders.

492
00:22:57,780 --> 00:23:00,382
They're settling and developing not only single structures,

493
00:23:00,442 --> 00:23:03,744
but managed to create a somewhat cohesive city from scraps.

494
00:23:04,764 --> 00:23:08,066
So we see a fuselage from a plane underperforming

495
00:23:08,306 --> 00:23:11,368
as its previous life was flying through the air,

496
00:23:11,428 --> 00:23:13,469
and now it's just simply a settlement.

497
00:23:14,030 --> 00:23:16,051
So there are a lot of things that indicate to us

498
00:23:16,191 --> 00:23:19,653
that this is a fallen from what it previously

499
00:23:19,713 --> 00:23:22,475
manufactured civilization, which is very interesting

500
00:23:22,515 --> 00:23:25,756
and very quick to get that information to the player.

501
00:23:26,937 --> 00:23:29,838
Rivet City creates a uniquely restrictive environment.

502
00:23:30,398 --> 00:23:33,239
The city is hosted on a retired aircraft carrier,

503
00:23:34,359 --> 00:23:36,960
which is a highly engineered vessel with precise openings.

504
00:23:37,540 --> 00:23:40,361
Unlike Megaton, these parts were not scrapped and customized.

505
00:23:41,261 --> 00:23:44,642
As a result, the citizens keep the structured lifestyle,

506
00:23:45,182 --> 00:23:47,563
and it feels restrictive, even to the extent

507
00:23:47,583 --> 00:23:50,084
that you must get permission to access it via the drawbridge.

508
00:23:51,804 --> 00:23:54,545
The mall leveraged inspiration from existing architecture

509
00:23:54,585 --> 00:23:55,645
fits very well here.

510
00:23:57,217 --> 00:23:59,299
Even if you haven't been to the United States Capitol,

511
00:23:59,639 --> 00:24:01,260
you know what it looks like, it's iconic.

512
00:24:02,061 --> 00:24:03,102
And even if you haven't seen it,

513
00:24:03,382 --> 00:24:05,784
the style of architecture is so formulaic,

514
00:24:06,585 --> 00:24:08,726
it's enough to demonstrate what's missing

515
00:24:08,806 --> 00:24:10,027
based on what remains.

516
00:24:10,768 --> 00:24:13,310
The practicality of imposing asymmetrical damage

517
00:24:13,350 --> 00:24:14,611
to a one symmetrical building

518
00:24:15,011 --> 00:24:16,832
has an inherent impact on the player.

519
00:24:18,234 --> 00:24:19,555
So given all that information,

520
00:24:19,615 --> 00:24:21,116
let's take a look at Tenpenny Tower.

