00:24:29,335 --> 00:24:31,056
the first massive moral decision you

526
00:24:31,116 --> 00:24:32,336
must make with your character.

527
00:24:32,996 --> 00:24:35,057
And spoiler alert, you're positioned

528
00:24:35,077 --> 00:24:38,578
to arm that bomb in Megaton City and destroy it.

529
00:24:39,578 --> 00:24:41,159
Breadcrumbs prepare you for this, though,

530
00:24:41,739 --> 00:24:43,899
learning how to arm the bomb, confirming the quest,

531
00:24:44,099 --> 00:24:45,220
bartering for the reward.

532
00:24:45,780 --> 00:24:48,241
And it will land you some seriously bad karma

533
00:24:48,281 --> 00:24:49,081
if you go through with it.

534
00:24:49,837 --> 00:24:52,139
Tenpenny Tower is where you push that button.

535
00:24:52,940 --> 00:24:55,703
This tower is also one of the best preserved buildings

536
00:24:55,763 --> 00:24:58,466
in the Fallout world, for a while at least,

537
00:24:59,827 --> 00:25:01,809
which creates an opportunity to represent

538
00:25:01,929 --> 00:25:03,631
what life was like in higher fidelity

539
00:25:03,992 --> 00:25:05,854
than any other exterior environment.

540
00:25:07,015 --> 00:25:09,437
It also has the opportunity to justify its longevity

541
00:25:09,918 --> 00:25:10,839
with building materials.

542
00:25:12,274 --> 00:25:14,075
And it may seem nitpicky, but all the rooms

543
00:25:14,155 --> 00:25:15,496
have kind of look like tunnels.

544
00:25:15,536 --> 00:25:16,377
They lack windows.

545
00:25:16,917 --> 00:25:19,019
And for the tallest building in the Wasteland,

546
00:25:19,059 --> 00:25:21,400
I would think that this would be kind of a selling point.

547
00:25:21,820 --> 00:25:25,843
But again, that's probably just because of engine limitations.

548
00:25:27,704 --> 00:25:29,225
And without a lot of sleuthing, we

549
00:25:29,265 --> 00:25:32,728
can look at the New Willard Hotel and see the similarities.

550
00:25:33,848 --> 00:25:37,391
It's a historically tall building in Washington, DC.

551
00:25:38,131 --> 00:25:40,573
And it's not a tower, though.

552
00:25:41,988 --> 00:25:44,089
And that's why I think Tenpenny looks a little bit squat.

553
00:25:45,289 --> 00:25:49,231
Early skyscrapers typically used primarily

554
00:25:49,451 --> 00:25:50,652
vertical articulation.

555
00:25:51,332 --> 00:25:52,833
Architects were actually over the moon

556
00:25:52,873 --> 00:25:54,113
about how high they could build,

557
00:25:54,274 --> 00:25:56,655
and as a result, couldn't even.

558
00:25:58,913 --> 00:26:03,697
About 100 years later, architects finally got over themselves and started exploring

559
00:26:03,837 --> 00:26:05,018
horizontal articulation.

560
00:26:05,078 --> 00:26:09,261
You can see the spandrel panels and floor plates articulating the iconic Lieberhaus,

561
00:26:09,962 --> 00:26:15,766
and the aqua tower provides modulation in the X axis at the cost of practicality because

562
00:26:15,826 --> 00:26:18,408
now it is actually just a radiator.

563
00:26:20,590 --> 00:26:24,532
The New Willard Hotel is actually a block building, which is why it's got that horizontal

564
00:26:24,552 --> 00:26:24,873
banding.

565
00:26:26,359 --> 00:26:29,361
Also, the hotel is massive compared to its neighbors.

566
00:26:29,582 --> 00:26:31,023
The city probably had restrictions

567
00:26:31,103 --> 00:26:33,866
on how tall a building could be on that plot of land.

568
00:26:34,266 --> 00:26:36,108
It's a very courteous building, though,

569
00:26:36,148 --> 00:26:37,970
because it gives back a little bit of space

570
00:26:38,050 --> 00:26:40,893
on that intersection, as you can see that chamfered corner.

571
00:26:41,776 --> 00:26:45,998
But then it does this thing that I have actually done myself.

572
00:26:46,199 --> 00:26:47,159
I feel really bad about this.

573
00:26:48,820 --> 00:26:51,422
That cornice, that balcony, actually just

574
00:26:51,482 --> 00:26:54,103
shields the view for the pedestrian.

575
00:26:54,544 --> 00:26:57,085
So it looks like the building's about 40 feet shorter.

576
00:26:57,525 --> 00:26:58,546
I've had to do this.

577
00:26:58,866 --> 00:27:00,187
I don't feel great about it.

578
00:27:01,027 --> 00:27:03,929
The vaulted roof structure also foregoes that upper edge.

579
00:27:04,510 --> 00:27:06,871
So it's hiding its penthouse floor

580
00:27:07,051 --> 00:27:08,852
as it's timidly approaching its footprint.

581
00:27:09,947 --> 00:27:12,087
So when we see Tenpenny Tower mimic these things,

582
00:27:12,187 --> 00:27:15,067
it appears ashamed of its size, fighting to appear shorter.

583
00:27:16,348 --> 00:27:18,508
We also don't see anything that could pick

584
00:27:18,528 --> 00:27:21,729
to another side of Tenpenny, outside of his dialogue.

585
00:27:22,589 --> 00:27:24,569
Something like strong 90 degree corners

586
00:27:24,649 --> 00:27:26,869
could imply a rigid, unchanging nature,

587
00:27:27,330 --> 00:27:30,050
as he's greeted with the wasteland, but refuses to adapt.

588
00:27:30,890 --> 00:27:32,490
Also, I'm still bummed about that Windows thing.

589
00:27:34,271 --> 00:27:36,731
Choosing reference material requires some insight

590
00:27:36,891 --> 00:27:39,052
on why it's working in its current context.

591
00:27:39,610 --> 00:27:42,872
In fact, you end up inheriting a lot of solutions

592
00:27:42,932 --> 00:27:44,073
to other people's problems.

593
00:27:45,574 --> 00:27:48,757
I could imagine a seemingly valid argument for this design

594
00:27:48,957 --> 00:27:53,020
as it relies on maybe existing in the palette of the Potomac.

595
00:27:54,101 --> 00:27:55,562
It's an existing building in the area.

596
00:27:55,602 --> 00:27:56,302
That would make sense.

597
00:27:56,983 --> 00:28:00,145
But it's easier to defend discrete moves and motives

598
00:28:00,325 --> 00:28:02,747
by referencing symbolic justification.

599
00:28:03,648 --> 00:28:05,950
This allows for more correct answers to your problem.

600
00:28:06,309 --> 00:28:07,890
as opposed to putting collaborators

601
00:28:08,110 --> 00:28:10,011
in a take it or leave it situation as well.

602
00:28:11,973 --> 00:28:13,794
I also saw this alternate concept art.

603
00:28:13,894 --> 00:28:16,335
I don't know why this didn't make it in.

604
00:28:16,776 --> 00:28:18,557
I could probably think of a thousand reasons

605
00:28:18,617 --> 00:28:19,578
why it couldn't make it in,

606
00:28:20,018 --> 00:28:22,519
but it does adhere better architecturally.

607
00:28:23,100 --> 00:28:26,542
So it has those 90 degree corners, which are really strong.

608
00:28:26,822 --> 00:28:29,584
It also has a bunch of different architectural styles,

609
00:28:29,644 --> 00:28:31,325
which is indicative of a single payer.

610
00:28:32,279 --> 00:28:34,599
And it does this wedding cake thing,

611
00:28:34,859 --> 00:28:37,700
where it builds slowly up to that decision point.

612
00:28:38,260 --> 00:28:40,181
And that could have a good correlation

613
00:28:40,241 --> 00:28:41,822
to the way you followed those breadcrumbs.

614
00:28:44,582 --> 00:28:47,643
Fallout ultimately does a fantastic job with storytelling.

615
00:28:48,103 --> 00:28:49,784
I spent 300 hours in this game,

616
00:28:50,104 --> 00:28:52,965
and I didn't feel constrained by an order of levels.

617
00:28:54,005 --> 00:28:55,366
So no matter what path I took,

618
00:28:56,246 --> 00:28:58,287
each did their part to further illustrate the world

619
00:28:58,527 --> 00:28:59,687
and the culture of the Wastelanders.

620
00:29:02,736 --> 00:29:04,597
Now, Inside was a remarkable game,

621
00:29:04,697 --> 00:29:06,539
and I will warn you, spoilers on this one.

622
00:29:06,699 --> 00:29:09,761
I'm saying that because it is a really good reveal.

623
00:29:10,602 --> 00:29:13,284
But the game relies on context and gameplay

624
00:29:13,304 --> 00:29:14,125
to reveal the plot.

625
00:29:15,246 --> 00:29:16,707
There are a lot of clever decisions

626
00:29:16,747 --> 00:29:19,589
which capitalize on the constraints and requirements.

627
00:29:20,930 --> 00:29:23,792
These decisions are leveraged to challenge the player

628
00:29:23,852 --> 00:29:25,633
to solve this meta puzzle.

629
00:29:26,145 --> 00:29:28,947
introducing a desire to know why you're here

630
00:29:28,988 --> 00:29:29,888
and what you're doing.

631
00:29:30,589 --> 00:29:35,474
Playdead uses this to set up and train the player

632
00:29:35,934 --> 00:29:37,055
under a certain set of rules

633
00:29:37,356 --> 00:29:39,758
and has them develop habits and strategies.

634
00:29:41,039 --> 00:29:43,041
This allows for the reversal at the finale

635
00:29:43,081 --> 00:29:44,643
to have much more of an impact.

636
00:29:44,903 --> 00:29:48,126
For architects, experience design and forced perspective

637
00:29:48,306 --> 00:29:50,468
are challenging to maintain for multiple hours.

638
00:29:52,119 --> 00:29:53,399
One building does come to mind,

639
00:29:53,519 --> 00:29:56,922
which provides prolonged empathetic experiences.

640
00:29:58,203 --> 00:30:01,745
Leibskins Jewish Museum in Berlin jars its occupants

641
00:30:01,805 --> 00:30:04,527
with subtly disorienting and harsh conditions

642
00:30:04,667 --> 00:30:06,188
in order to simulate the toll

643
00:30:06,308 --> 00:30:07,769
an environment can take on a human.

644
00:30:08,910 --> 00:30:11,391
The color palette is reduced to mid-gray tones,

645
00:30:11,812 --> 00:30:15,154
forcing occupants to use light to distinguish elements.

646
00:30:15,894 --> 00:30:17,516
Soft shadows strain the viewer

647
00:30:17,596 --> 00:30:19,077
to distinguish similar elements,

648
00:30:19,197 --> 00:30:20,738
and harsh lights produce.

649
00:30:21,164 --> 00:30:25,067
stressful impairment on eyes by providing too much contrast.

650
00:30:26,429 --> 00:30:29,392
Narrow windows consistently cover the exterior,

651
00:30:29,472 --> 00:30:30,993
providing different level of lights

652
00:30:31,393 --> 00:30:34,036
through the same mechanic, that thin rectangular void.

653
00:30:34,857 --> 00:30:36,819
By rotating those, you've actually created

654
00:30:36,879 --> 00:30:40,843
a variety of conditions which can be used

655
00:30:40,883 --> 00:30:43,225
to do that subtle and stark thing

656
00:30:43,485 --> 00:30:45,427
that was messing with people's eyes.

657
00:30:47,310 --> 00:30:49,753
Many museums rely on layout and lighting

658
00:30:49,833 --> 00:30:51,635
to break up displays in an attempt

659
00:30:51,715 --> 00:30:54,598
to help viewers read for more than comprehension,

660
00:30:55,038 --> 00:30:55,919
but empathy.

661
00:30:56,400 --> 00:30:58,562
You're asking the visitor to learn a lot

662
00:30:58,762 --> 00:31:01,284
by giving them breaks between exhibits.

663
00:31:01,325 --> 00:31:03,787
You allow them to rebuild their stamina and learn more.

664
00:31:05,043 --> 00:31:07,184
These sharp corners provide an uneasy feeling

665
00:31:07,204 --> 00:31:08,465
throughout the entire journey,

666
00:31:08,825 --> 00:31:11,227
granting temporary reprieve between spaces,

667
00:31:11,307 --> 00:31:13,188
but not letting the visitor feel rested

668
00:31:13,508 --> 00:31:16,410
or have a clear path forward to the end.

669
00:31:17,170 --> 00:31:18,531
Leaveskin treats the museum

670
00:31:18,691 --> 00:31:20,152
as an extension of the collection,

671
00:31:20,612 --> 00:31:22,053
a machine for creating feeling,

672
00:31:22,673 --> 00:31:24,434
not just something people move through.

673
00:31:26,536 --> 00:31:28,637
Inside forces a reckoning with the players,

674
00:31:28,697 --> 00:31:29,538
seemingly at ease.

675
00:31:30,625 --> 00:31:33,147
The player must use spatial and visual indicators

676
00:31:33,207 --> 00:31:35,169
to discern meaning about their experience,

677
00:31:35,689 --> 00:31:39,272
like lighting, building layout, material characteristics,

678
00:31:39,593 --> 00:31:40,934
and area of effect.

679
00:31:42,195 --> 00:31:43,956
By providing high-fidelity details,

680
00:31:43,996 --> 00:31:46,398
the onus falls on the player to distinguish content.

681
00:31:46,939 --> 00:31:48,760
In Playdead's previous hit, Limbo,

682
00:31:49,220 --> 00:31:51,662
we see a blur as things fall out of focus.

683
00:31:52,203 --> 00:31:55,886
Inside, crisp backdrops indicate their value

684
00:31:56,246 --> 00:31:58,228
as a narrative element.

685
00:31:58,288 --> 00:31:59,829
There's something that's important to you.

686
00:32:01,807 --> 00:32:03,969
They also work to codify planes of action.

687
00:32:04,489 --> 00:32:06,491
Early in the game, the smaller challenges

688
00:32:06,631 --> 00:32:09,433
train the player to focus on opportunities presented

689
00:32:09,473 --> 00:32:12,375
in a single plane while referencing mid-ground

690
00:32:12,395 --> 00:32:14,096
and background for information.

691
00:32:15,097 --> 00:32:17,158
So the scenes can actually be dissected.

692
00:32:19,480 --> 00:32:23,122
So in this one, we see that we have control over the chicks,

693
00:32:23,463 --> 00:32:25,164
and we also have control over the lever.

694
00:32:25,704 --> 00:32:26,645
That's in the foreground.

695
00:32:26,725 --> 00:32:28,446
That's lit by that lamp.

696
00:32:29,346 --> 00:32:32,768
as soon as we pull the lever, we lose control of the chicks

697
00:32:32,848 --> 00:32:34,088
as they go into the background.

698
00:32:34,709 --> 00:32:35,169
Poor things.

699
00:32:37,490 --> 00:32:39,551
The same can be said about this scene

700
00:32:39,631 --> 00:32:42,352
where you have control over your player in the foreground

701
00:32:42,653 --> 00:32:45,914
and start to learn how to control the background.

702
00:32:47,935 --> 00:32:49,436
But they keep the plane separated

703
00:32:49,496 --> 00:32:50,877
as you don't have full control yet.

704
00:32:53,498 --> 00:32:55,539
So we're gonna use that word again, phenomenology.

705
00:32:56,421 --> 00:32:59,844
It's when you're fed information and it stays below the level of consciousness.

706
00:33:00,524 --> 00:33:03,546
The subtlety of clues is actually held as a datum in this game.

707
00:33:04,187 --> 00:33:07,970
The player's consciousness actually fluctuates when they're tasked with challenges.

708
00:33:09,111 --> 00:33:13,974
Platforming challenges come in waves, switching you between survival and understanding the

709
00:33:14,015 --> 00:33:14,315
levels.

710
00:33:15,516 --> 00:33:18,518
The environment is consistently broadcasting clues

711
00:33:18,638 --> 00:33:21,719
to a player on a basis of whether they're in control

712
00:33:21,760 --> 00:33:22,540
or following along.

713
00:33:23,200 --> 00:33:24,821
So two different players would actually have

714
00:33:24,841 --> 00:33:27,062
two vastly different experiences

715
00:33:28,343 --> 00:33:30,384
and maybe get the same story out of it

716
00:33:30,785 --> 00:33:33,986
even though they've been presented with the same material.

717
00:33:34,006 --> 00:33:34,046
So.

718
00:33:37,707 --> 00:33:39,487
this is like a personal problem for me,

719
00:33:39,528 --> 00:33:40,888
but I'm not good at platforming.

720
00:33:41,328 --> 00:33:43,009
And this was a really hard part for me.

721
00:33:43,529 --> 00:33:45,871
I didn't even notice the people in the background

722
00:33:45,911 --> 00:33:46,891
that were watching me do this,

723
00:33:47,171 --> 00:33:48,652
which completely changes the scene.

724
00:33:49,392 --> 00:33:50,973
And then if I was even better at it,

725
00:33:51,133 --> 00:33:53,234
I didn't notice that bus in the background

726
00:33:53,254 --> 00:33:53,935
that brought them,

727
00:33:54,155 --> 00:33:57,336
which indicates an institutional portion of their presence.

728
00:33:58,537 --> 00:33:59,897
And that would have completely changed

729
00:33:59,937 --> 00:34:01,858
the way I perceived that moment in the game.

730
00:34:04,880 --> 00:34:08,000
They also do this great thing where the materiality shifts

731
00:34:08,681 --> 00:34:11,501
from something seemingly less formal and rustic

732
00:34:11,981 --> 00:34:14,222
to something maybe a little bit more industrial

733
00:34:14,582 --> 00:34:16,783
and then gets curved glass at some point

734
00:34:16,963 --> 00:34:18,223
and it has a scientific look.

735
00:34:19,343 --> 00:34:21,584
A life cycle that a lot of technology has

736
00:34:21,644 --> 00:34:25,685
from origin to militarization or monetization

737
00:34:25,765 --> 00:34:27,565
such as airplanes for instance.

738
00:34:29,602 --> 00:34:31,082
I don't have many critiques of this game.

739
00:34:31,503 --> 00:34:34,304
It masters the use of passive and active design cues

740
00:34:34,624 --> 00:34:36,365
by fluctuating the level of attention

741
00:34:36,726 --> 00:34:40,328
the player has the capacity to spend outside of platforming.

742
00:34:41,228 --> 00:34:43,690
This provides an allegory for seeing the forest

743
00:34:43,730 --> 00:34:47,092
beyond the trees, which ends up being tough to simulate.

744
00:34:50,253 --> 00:34:51,974
So going back on that initial thought,

745
00:34:52,635 --> 00:34:54,576
designing for an authentic experience.

746
00:34:58,711 --> 00:35:02,293
And I think it boils down to who the perceived designer is.

747
00:35:03,533 --> 00:35:05,234
The environment has the opportunity

748
00:35:05,374 --> 00:35:07,295
to feel as if it's been designed

749
00:35:07,335 --> 00:35:08,756
by an inhabitant of the world.

750
00:35:09,496 --> 00:35:12,018
Studying architecture and building taste

751
00:35:12,158 --> 00:35:14,259
can improve the ease at which you design

752
00:35:14,579 --> 00:35:15,780
for a varied context.

753
00:35:16,740 --> 00:35:19,161
Another way to build taste is by looking at the way

754
00:35:19,322 --> 00:35:21,803
directors use existing buildings as sets.

755
00:35:23,884 --> 00:35:26,565
Directors frame the camera and change lightings

756
00:35:26,605 --> 00:35:27,806
to recharacterize a space.

757
00:35:29,288 --> 00:35:32,071
These settings sculpt the general perception of spaces

758
00:35:32,572 --> 00:35:35,334
because it feels like they were built just for these moments.

759
00:35:36,856 --> 00:35:38,898
So the way the Bradbury building felt

760
00:35:39,318 --> 00:35:43,682
when you're watching Blade Runner versus 500 Days of Summer

761
00:35:43,783 --> 00:35:45,144
is dramatically different.

762
00:35:46,278 --> 00:35:50,243
And it has a lot to do with the closeness of the characters

763
00:35:50,323 --> 00:35:51,144
to the environment.

764
00:35:51,585 --> 00:35:53,447
It also has a lot to do with the special effects

765
00:35:53,467 --> 00:35:54,047
that are involved.

766
00:35:54,628 --> 00:35:56,310
So there's a lot of things that you can learn

767
00:35:56,330 --> 00:36:01,076
that aren't necessarily even in the structure of a building

768
00:36:01,456 --> 00:36:04,439
that can be conveyed through a variety of means.

769
00:36:06,579 --> 00:36:10,421
Further mastery of this medium also allows movie set designers

770
00:36:10,501 --> 00:36:15,184
to propose new contexts for style learned or adapted

771
00:36:15,264 --> 00:36:16,705
from a real built structure.

772
00:36:17,505 --> 00:36:21,687
So we see Frank Lloyd Wright's Ennis House actually performing

773
00:36:21,767 --> 00:36:25,810
very well in the new environment of Blade Runner

774
00:36:25,930 --> 00:36:27,190
in Deckard's apartment.

775
00:36:31,513 --> 00:36:34,034
If you do like books, I've come up with a pretty good list.

776
00:36:34,783 --> 00:36:37,964
The first book is a good place to start

777
00:36:38,084 --> 00:36:40,185
if you're looking for where this line of study could take you.

778
00:36:41,165 --> 00:36:44,366
The next two are a lot, and it might take some rereading,

779
00:36:44,826 --> 00:36:46,926
but will certainly broaden your horizons.

780
00:36:47,807 --> 00:36:50,347
That last one is like our version of Google.

781
00:36:51,007 --> 00:36:54,268
It can help you find critics or authors sorted by topics.

782
00:36:56,749 --> 00:36:58,969
But it's nothing compared to the recommended reading that

783
00:36:59,009 --> 00:37:00,270
came with the original Sims game.

784
00:37:01,010 --> 00:37:02,610
I cherry-picked the ones that were literally

785
00:37:02,670 --> 00:37:03,510
part of my curriculum.

786
00:37:05,672 --> 00:37:08,293
